window.BOOK_DATA = {"intro": ["Agriculture", "and Nutrition", "Grade 9", "Learner's Book", "Table of Contents", "1.0 Conservation of Resources ................................................................. 1", "1.1 Conserving Animal Feed: Hay .....................................................................1", "1.2 Conserving Leftover Food ........................................................................... 9", "1.3 Integrated Farming ....................................................................................18", "2.0 Food Production Processes ................................................................ 23", "2.1 Organic Gardening ................................................................................... 23", "2.2 Storage of Crop Produce .......................................................................... 42", "2.3 Cooking: Using Flour Mixtures ................................................................. 47", "3.0 Hygiene Practices ............................................................................. 55", "3.1 Cleaning Waste Disposal Facilities ........................................................... 55", "3.2 Disinfecting Clothing and Household Articles .......................................... 63", "4.0 Production Techniques ...................................................................... 72", "4.1 Grafting in Plants ..................................................................................... 72", "4.2 Homemade Sun Dryer .............................................................................. 76"], "pages": [{"page": 1, "text": "In this strand, we will learn how to conserve forage as hay so as to solve the problem ofscarce animal feeds during drought seasons. We will also learn how to prepare leftoverfoods in our homes for consumption to avoid wastage. Finally, we will learn how torecycle resources within the farm through integrated farming to reduce costs.\nConserving Animal Feed: Hay\nDuring long and short rainy seasons, there is plenty of forage crops (pastures and foddercrops) for domestic animals in most parts of the country. However, during droughtseasons, there is scarcity of forage crops leading to starvation and death of the animals.\nIn pastoralist areas, farmers migrate their animals to faraway places in search of pasture.\nThis sometimes leads to communal conflicts as animals compete to graze on limitedpastures. Learning how to conserve excess forage can cushion households from foddershortages during dry seasons. We will learn how to conserve forage through making hay.\nMethods of conserving forage\nForage are plants which grow naturally or are planted for feeding livestock animals.\nThe forage plants which are grazed directly by livestock are calledpastureswhile thosewhich are harvested and then fed to livestock are calledfodder crops\n. We will focus onmethods of conserving forage as hay, namely baled hay, stacking hay and standing hay.\nActivity 1\nLet us talk (in pairs)\n1.\nWhat is hay?\n2.\nWhat forage crops are suitable for making hay?\n3.\nWhich animals feed on hay?\n4.\nShare your ideas and experiences on how hay is prepared.\net us\nLean\nLr\nHay refers to forage that has been cut and then dried to about 15 to 20% moisturecontent. Grasses make good hay. However, the type of forage material should beconsidered when selecting the forage for hay making. For example, grasses with thin\nCONSERVATION OF RESOURCES"}, {"page": 2, "text": "stems are preferred to those with thick stems. Grasses such as napier grass may notmake good hay because their thick stems may not loose moisture easily unlike Boma\nRhodes grass.\nOther forage crops that may be used as hay include lucerne, desmodium, Sudan grass,\nforage sorghum, pear millet, oat, barley and rice straws.\nPear millet\nBoma Rhodes\nSudan grass\nA. Preparing and baling hay\nHow is hay prepared for baling?\nActivity 2\nLet us go digital\n1.\nUsing a digital device, search for information or video clips on how to preparebaled hay for storage. Your search should focus on the following:\na)\nSuitable forage crops for hay.\nb)\nBest stage for harvesting the forage.\nc)\nBest weather conditions when harvesting forage and preparing it for hay.\nd)\nCuring process (preparation) after cutting the forage crop to maintainquality of hay.\ne)\nHow to bale hay.\nf)\nHow to store the hay to reduce loss of nutrients.\ng)\nFactors that affect quality of hay.\n2.\nAlternatively, seek the information from a resource person who understandshow hay is prepared.\n3.\nRecord important points on hay making and discuss with the rest of the class.\nab\nca\nbc"}, {"page": 3, "text": "et us\nLean\nLr\nForage crops for hay are harvested at the flowering stage because that is whenconcentration of nutrients is at the highest. The weather during the harvesting andpreparation stage should be hot and dry.\nWhen harvesting manually, a sickle or scythe is used to cut the forage.\nHarvesting forage for hay making\nThe cut forage is left to sun dry (wilt) for 2 to 3 days depending on the prevailingweather conditions. Within that period, the forage is spread evenly or turned using arake a few times to ensure uniform drying. The forage at that point should not breakeasily.\nSpreading hay to ensure uniform drying\nab"}, {"page": 4, "text": "Dried hay should be gathered and put in a wooden box measuring 75 cm by 50 cmby 40 cm and compressed manually.\nCompacting hay\nThe hay should be tied with sisal or synthetic twine and then stored in bales in a raisedand well aerated shed away from rain and water.\nBailed hay in a shed\nNote:\nForage planted on small scale can also be cut using hand held mowers insteadof sickles. However, forage planted on large scale is harvested using tractor drawnmowers and baled using machines."}, {"page": 5, "text": "B.\nConserving crop residues by stacking method\nAfter harvesting crops, crop remains such as straws and stovers can be conserved forconsumption by some livestock animals. How are such crop residues conserved?\nActivity 3\nLet us talk (in pairs)\nDuring a visit to a farm, Grade 9 learners observed some stovers of maize stored bystacking method after the maize grains had been harvested.\nStacked maize stovers\n1.\nWhich other forage crops are given to livestock as dry crop residues?\n2.\nWhy should the stacked stovers have conical shape at the top?\n3.\nWhat precautions should be taken to ensure the stovers do not lose theirnutritive value?\n4.\nCompare the quality of stovers with baled hay.\n5.\nShare with the rest of the class.\nC. Standing forage or hay\n1.\nWhat is standing hay?\n2.\nWhy is standing hay important?\nActivity 4\nLet us talk (in pairs)\nWhile searching on various methods of conserving hay, Grade 9 learners learnt that apiece of land can be planted with forage crops and left aside for the forage to grow."}, {"page": 6, "text": "During the dry season, animals are allowed to graze on the forage. Such method offorage conservation is called standing hay.\nCattle grazing on standing hay or forage\n1.\nSuggest why the method of conservation described above is called standing hay.\n2.\nSuggest one advantage of standing hay.\n3.\nSuggest one disadvantage of such a method of forage conservation whencompared to the previous methods that you have learned so far (Baled hayand stacked hay).\n4.\nShare your ideas with the rest of the class.\nActivity 5\nProject on forage conservation (in groups)\n1.\nIdentify where to obtain forage crops for conservation in your locality.\n2.\nDecide which method of forage conservation (baled hay or staked hay) will besuitable for the forage crops that are available in your locality.\n3.\nList all the tools, equipment and materials that you will require and discuss withyour teacher how they will be availed.\n4.\nHarvest and conserve forage of your choice using any of the two methods.\nNote:\nSince this project is meant to showcase the skills learnt so far, each groupis required to conserve a small amount of forage (about 5 to10 kg in weight).\n5.\nIn your journal, record your experiences and any lessons learnt while carryingout the project."}, {"page": 7, "text": "Activity 6\nLet us talk (in groups)\n1.\nDiscuss the importance of conserving forage at household level.\n2.\nDiscuss how to ensure that hay is of good quality.\n3.\nWrite your suggestions on a manila sheet and present your work during gallerywalk.\nTake Home Activity\nUse the knowledge and skills acquired to discuss with your parent or guardian how toconserve hay for feeding animals such as sheep, goats, cattle and rabbits.\net us\nLean\nLr\nForage can be preserved as baled hay, stacked stovers or standing hay. Conservationof forage helps to:\na.\nProvide feed to animals during the dry season.\nb.\nEnsure forage is well distributed throughout the year.\nc.\nEnsure better utilisation of available land.\nd.\nProvide income to households when excess hay is sold.\nBaled hay is of higher quality in terms of nutritive value compared to stovers andstanding hay. The quality of hay is determined by factors such as:\na.\nThe type of forage which is harvested. For example, grasses with thin stems areof high quality.\nb.\nStage of harvesting. When grasses are at the flowering stage, the quality offorage is high since nutrients are at high concentration.\nc.\nHow well the cut pasture or fodder is dried.\nd.\nLength of the drying period. Prolonged drying lowers the quality of hay sincenutrients are lost through breakdown of chlorophyll and carotene. This is shownby bleaching of hay. High moisture content of hay at the time of storage canlead to fermentation and growth of mould, hence loss of nutrients.\ne.\nWeather conditions during harvesting and drying period. There should be no rain.\nf.\nCondition of the storage structure. Hay should be kept in a cool, dry, wellventilated and roofed structure.\ng.\nInclusion of legume pasture such as lucerne or desmodium in the grass pasture.\nLegume pastures have more protein than grass pastures."}, {"page": 8, "text": "Assess yourself\n1.\na) You have been given a task of harvesting Bhoma Rhode grass which has beenplanted on a small plot of land. You are also required to conserve it as hay inbales. Describe how you will carry out the assigned task.\nb) Described other ways of conserving the fodder.\n2.\nA Grade 9 learner observed that some stored hay had moulds. After some time,\nthe hay was rotten and therefore unfit for feeding the cattle.\na) Suggest possible reasons why the hay was in that situation.\nb) Give other factors that may affect the quality of hay.\n3.\nWhy should farmers conserve forage?"}, {"page": 9, "text": "Conserving Leftover Foods\nImportance of conserving leftover foods at home\nDespite our best efforts in meal planning, having leftover food after meals is inevitable.\nThis can lead to food wastage. Therefore, it is important to manage leftover foodseffectively to avoid wastage of food.\nActivity 1\nLet us talk (in pairs)\n1.\nHave you ever had leftover food after taking a meal?\n2.\nShare your experiences on what you did with the leftover food.\nActivity 2\nLet us talk (in groups)\nStudy the pictures below and answer the questions that follow.\nLet us makeugalitoast forbreakfast usingthis leftoverugali\n.\nPlease take this food so that youand your family can have it forsupper. We have a lot of leftoverfood from the party.\n1.\nDescribe how each of the ways shown in the pictures help to conserve leftoverfoods.\n2.\nBrainstorm on hygiene practices that should be observed when handling leftoverfoods.\n3.\nShare your ideas in class.\nab\ncc\nab"}, {"page": 10, "text": "et us\nLean\nLr\nConserving leftover foods means taking steps to avoid wasting extra food after a meal.\nThis involves storing leftover foods properly, sharing them with friends or relatives andusing creative ways to include them in new meals.\nLeftover foods should be stored in clean containers that are covered well, then storedin a refrigerator or cool place. This is to avoid food contamination which may leadto food poisoning.\nActivity 3\nLet us talk (in groups)\nRead the following story and answer the questions that follow.\nOne Sunday, Susan, a Grade 9 learner, was left at home with her two younger siblingssince their parents had gone to visit their grandparents. When it was time for lunch,\nher younger siblings began to express their hunger, asking Susan for something to eat.\nSusan remembered there were leftovers in the fridge from the previous nights dinner;\nrice, stewed beef and vegetables. Instead of ordering for fast foods, she saw this asan opportunity to turn the leftovers into a delicious homemade meal.\nSusan heated the leftover rice and beef in a pan and added soy sauce for flavour. Next,\nshe tossed in the vegetables, creating an aromatic stir fry. Once the meal was ready,\nSusan served her siblings. To her delight, her siblings loved the meal. This proved thatwith creativity, leftovers can be turned into a delicious and satisfying meal.\n1.\nWhich values did Susans actions teach her younger siblings?\n2.\nFrom the story, what are the benefits of turning leftovers into a new dish?\n3.\nExplain other benefits of conserving leftover foods at home.\n4.\nShare your ideas in class.\net us\nLean\nLr\nThe following are the importance of conserving leftover meals at home:\n1.\nPrevents wastage of food: Reheating dishes allows one to eat leftover food whichensures that there is no wastage of food.\n2.\nSaves money: This is because a meal can be produced without buying ingredients.\n3.\nSaves energy: Reheating dishes does not use a lot of fuel.\n4.\nSaves labour: Since reheating dishes require little to no preparation, it savesthe effort that would have been used for normal food preparation and cooking.\n5.\nSaves time: Reheating dishes is faster compared to cooking a meal."}, {"page": 11, "text": "Preparing leftover foods to avoid wastage\nWe can prepare leftover foods by reheating or recooking. Reheating involves subjectingfoods to high temperatures to warm them for eating. Recooking involves creating anotherdish using leftover foods.\nActivity 4\nLet us talk (in pairs)\nManje wants to prepare supper using leftover rice. However, he cannot rememberhow long the food has stayed in the refrigerator. The rice also has an unusual smell.\n1.\nWhat should Manje do? Explain.\n2.\nWhat factors should one consider when using leftover foods?\n3.\nShare your ideas in class.\nCaution\nThrow away leftover foods that show signs of spoilage such as foul smell, unusualcolour or unusual texture.\nActivity 5\nLets go digital\n1.\nUse digital or print resources to search and compile recipes on how to preparevarious leftover foods at home.\n2.\nYou may also write down recipes used to prepare leftover foods that you useat home.\n3.\nShare the recipes in class.\nActivity 6\nLet us do (in groups)\nLeftoverugali\nRequirements\nLeftoverugali\n, knife, margarine, frying pan, source of heat, a clean plate and matchbox.\nSteps to follow\n1.\nSlice theugaliinto thin slices."}, {"page": 12, "text": "2.\nSpread margarine on both sides of the slicedugali\n.\n3.\nHeat a frying pan.\n4.\nPlace theugalispread with margarine onto the hot frying pan.\n5.\nFry until both sides are browned.\n6.\nServe for breakfast on a clean plate. You may serve alongside suitableaccompaniments such as tea and an egg.\nActivity 7\nLet us do (in groups)\nLeftoverugali\nRequirements\nLeftover ugali, 1 egg, salt, tongs or a spoon, cooking oil, frying pan, source of heat, aclean plate and matchbox.\nSteps to follow\n1.\nSlice theugaliinto thin slices."}, {"page": 13, "text": "2.\nBeat the egg in a bowl and add some salt to taste.\n3.\nCoat the slices ofugaliwith the beaten egg.\n4.\nShallow fry both sides of theugalislices until light brown.\n5.\nServe when hot on a clean plate.\nActivity 8\nLet us do (in groups)\nLeftoverchapati\nRequirements\nLeftoverchapati\n, source of heat, matchbox, pan, stew or tea.\nSteps to follow\n1.\nDry fry thechapation a moderate hot pan.\n2.\nServe with tea or stew.\nActivity 9\nLet us do (in groups)\nLeftover boiled arrowroots\nRequirements\nLeftover boiled arrowroots, cooking oil, matchbox, source of heat, slotted spoon, cleanplate, a deep frying pan, colander or bowl and absorbent paper."}, {"page": 14, "text": "Steps to follow\n1.\nPut some cooking oil in a frying pan and place it on the source of heat.\n2.\nHeat the oil until it is hot enough. Using a slotted spoon, lower the leftoverboiled arrowroots gently into the hot oil to avoid the oil from splashing.\n3.\nFry the arrowroots while gently turning them until they turn golden brown incolour.\n4.\nRemove the deep fried arrowroots from the pan using a slotted spoon and placethem in a colander or bowl lined with absorbent paper.\n5.\nServe the arrowroots on a clean plate. You may serve with a suitableaccompaniment such as tea.\nActivity 10\nLet us do (in groups)\nLeftovergitheri\nRequirements\nLeftovergitheri\n, pumpkin leaves, cooking oil, potatoes, salt,\nsufuriawith a lid, jug,\npotato masher or cooking stick, source of heat and matchbox.\nSteps to follow\n1.\nPeel potatoes and wash them in clean water.\n2.\nPut the peeled potatoes in boiling water and place the pumpkin leaves on topof the potatoes so that they can steam as the potatoes boil."}, {"page": 15, "text": "3.\nWhen the potatoes are almost cooked, add thegitheriand allow it to warm.\n4.\nOnce thegitheriis hot, drain the excess water in a jug.\n5.\nAdd salt and mash using the potato masher or cooking stick.\n6.\nIf themukimogets too dry, add the drained liquid.\n7.\nPut themukimoin a serving dish.\n8.\nServe themukimoon a clean plate when hot.\n9.\nYou may serve alongside a suitable accompaniment such as beef or chicken stew."}, {"page": 16, "text": "Activity 11\nLet us do (in groups)\nLeftover rice\nRequirements\n2 cups leftover rice, 3 eggs, 1 onion, cooking oil, pan, matchbox and source of heat.\nSteps to follow\n1.\nPeel the onion and wash it.\n2.\nChop the onion. Fry the onion in the oil until golden brown.\n3.\nBeat the eggs in a bowl.\n4.\nAdd the leftover rice and beaten egg to the fried onions. Stir continuously usinga fork to prevent the mixture from sticking on the pan.\n5.\nWhen ready, serve it on a clean plate.\n6.\nYou may serve with a suitable accompaniment such as kale, spinach or cabbage."}, {"page": 17, "text": "Note:\nReheat leftover stews as they are. You may add some chopped coriander toimprove the flavour.\nTake Home Activity\n1.\nPrepare leftover foods at home and serve it to your family members.\n2.\nShare your experiences in class.\nActivity 12\nLet us talk (in pairs)\nHow many times can one reheat leftover food? Explain your reasons.\net us\nLean\nLr\nNever reheat food more than once. This may cause denaturing (destruction) of foodnutrients and lead to growth of micro-organisms.\nActivity 12\nLet us debate\n1.\nOrganise the classroom for a debate.\n2.\nDebate on the following topic:\nFamilies should prioritise conserving leftoverfoods to prevent food wastage at home\n.\n3.\nRecord points made during the presentation.\nAssess yourself\n1.\nGrade 9 learners made posters to educate the community on the importanceof conserving leftover foods at home. Which points are they likely to includein their posters?\n2.\nWhich of the following statements are true regarding factors to consider whenusing leftover foods? Explain reasons for you responses.\na)\nLeftover foods should be stored in clean airtight containers.\nb)\nLeftover foods should be reheated repeatedly.\nc)\nSpoilt leftover foods should be prepared to avoid wastage.\nd)\nReheating leftover food should not be overdone.\n3.\nYou have the following leftover foods. Explain how you would use them toprepare a meal.\na)\nBoiled potatoes.\nb)\nFried chicken."}, {"page": 18, "text": "Integrated Farming\nOne agricultural enterprise produces waste which can be considered as a resource orinput in another agricultural enterprise. For this reason, some households practise acombination of several agricultural enterprises in the same compound in a way that theymutually benefit each other and conserve available resources.\nMeaning of integrated farming\nActivity 1\nLet us talk (in pairs)\n1.\nShare your understanding of the termintegrated farming\n.\n2.\na) Discuss some of the possible farming enterprises that may be practised inintegrated farming in your locality.\nb) Discuss how the farming enterprises that you have suggested help in theconservation of resources in the environment.\n3.\nPresent to the rest of the class.\net us\nLean\nLr\nIntegrated farming is an approach to farming whereby different but compatibleagricultural enterprises are practised in a unit of land. For example, dairy farming,\npoultry farming, rabbit rearing, fish farming, bee keeping, crop farming and tree growingmay be practised in a single unit of land.\nComponents of an integrated farm\nActivity 2\nLet us go digital\n1.\nUsing a digital device, observe video clips on an integrated farming system.\nAlternatively, read relevant print materials on components and importance ofintegrated farming.\n2.\nSummarise key points on:\na.\nComponents of an integrated farming system.\nb.\nThe importance of integrated farming."}, {"page": 19, "text": "Activity 3\nLet us do (in groups)\n1.\nWith the guidance of your teacher, visit a household that practises integratedfarming.\n2.\nObserve how the various farming activities complement each other.\n3.\nFind out from the members of the household what they considered beforeestablishing an integrated farm.\n4.\nWrite a short report of your findings from the visit.\n5.\nPresent your findings in class.\nExamples of an integrated farm\nActivity 4\nLet us do (in groups)\nStudy the pictures below which show various farming activities being practised on a\n0.4 hectare piece of land.\n1.\nExplain why the various farming enterprises constitute integrated farming.\nHint:\nShow how they can benefit each other.\n2.\nSuggest other examples of farming enterprises that can make an integrated farm."}, {"page": 20, "text": "Designing a model of an integrated farm\nActivity 5\nLet us do (in groups)\n1.\nMake a model of an integrated farming for a small unit of land or a large farm.\n2.\nDiscuss appropriate farming activities to be included in your integrated farmingmodel. You may choose a combination of enterprises from the following: dairyfarming, sheep and goat farming, poultry farming, pig farming, rabbit farming,\nsh rearing, bee keeping, vegetable farming, fruit farming, cereal production,\nlegume production, fodder production, tree farming, among others.\n3.\nOn a manila sheet, draw a diagram to illustrate an integrated farming system.\nStudy the example shown and discuss how resources are conserved within thefarm.\nDairy cattle\nGrass pasture, maize and sorghum for silage\nFish pond\nFodder legumes and shrubs\nHints:\n-\nCattle manure can be used to fertilise a fish pond, hence allow growth ofvarious organisms such as planktons which supply food to fish.\n-\nSlurry from cattle and waste water from fish pond are used to improve soilfertility leading to high production of grass pasture, maize and sorghumwhich are then used to feed cattle.\n-\nFodder legumes and shrubs fix nitrogen into the soil. Thus, if planted togetherwith grass, maize and silage, soil fertility is improved leading to more feedsfor the cattle.\n-\nFodder legumes and shrubs are sources of proteins for cattle and fish.\n4.\nYou may also create a farm model at the back of the classroom or any othersuitable place in the school compound. Show several farming activities thatconstitute integrated farming. You may use materials such as clay soil, plasticine,\nwater, offcuts, timber, stones, cartons, cardboards, used polythene sheets, usedpapers, common vegetation in the area, among others. All the group membersshould be assigned roles.\n5.\nExplain the importance of your proposed integrated farming model to otherlearners in your class."}, {"page": 21, "text": "Importance of integrated farminget us\nLean\nLr\nSome of the benefits of integrated farming include:\na)\nEfficient utilisation of resources and hence reduction of production costs. Forexample, livestock wastes and fish waste water can be used as manure for cropswhile crop residues and fodder crops are used as livestock feed.\nb)\nSoil conservation through use of organic manures and recycling of nutrientsbetween crops, livestock and fish. In addition, when trees are grown on land,\ntheir roots hold the soil firmly thus preventing soil erosion by water.\nc)\nPromotion of environmental sustainability. For example, the use of chemicalfertilisers which pollute soil is reduced when organic manures generated in thefarm are used in the garden. Animal waste, crop residues and wood within thefarm can be used as sources of energy at the household level thus minimisingthe use of fossil fuels which pollute our environment.\nd)\nDiversification of income sources throughout the year.\ne)\nPromotion of food security and nutrition. Practising different farming activitiesreduce the risk of total food production failure.\nf)\nHigh yields per unit area.\nBefore practising integrated farming, it is important to consider various factorssuch as availability of land, labour, resources and skills to manage the variousenterprises; suitability of ecological conditions (rainfall, temperature, soil type andother environmental factors) to the proposed farming enterprises and cost of runningthe various enterprises.\nAssess yourself\n1.\nWhen searching for information on components of integrated farming, Grade\n9 learners came across an integrated crop-livestock farming system consistingof livestock (cattle, poultry), crops (maize, sorghum and sugarcane) and foddercrops (napier grass, rhodes grass, lucerne).\na)\nExplain how the above components of the integrated farm conserveavailable resources.\nb)\nWhat other benefits does such a farming system have over one whereonly crop farming or livestock farming is practised?"}, {"page": 22, "text": "2.\nDuring a field visit to a neighbouring farm, Grade 9 learners observed thefollowing:\na)\nHuge piles of unused rabbit waste next to the rabbit hutches.\nb)\nRabbits depended on fresh grass which was being obtained from theneighbouring farms.\nc)\nThere was excessive use of pesticides. This resulted to few bees in theorchard and vegetables sections of the garden during the floweringseason.\nd)\nThe different crops in the garden were stunted and unhealthy.\nSuggest how the farmer may apply the knowledge and skills of integrated farmingto solve the above challenges.\n3.\nDiscuss this statement: Integrated farming enhances environmental sustainability."}, {"page": 23, "text": "We will learn how to grow crops through organic gardening practices and how to storecrop produce in order to prevent post-harvest losses. In addition, we will learn how toprepare food products from various flour mixtures.\nOrganic Gardening\nSome of the conventional gardening practices can have negative effects on human healthand the environment. In addition, they are costly and thus unsustainable in the longrun. Are you aware of such practices? What is the alternative to such practices? Onealternative is organic gardening. We will learn how organic gardening can be practisedin order to reduce such problems and ensure sustainable food production.\nMeaning of organic gardening\nActivity 1\nLet us go digital\n1.\nUsing a digital device, search the meaning of organic gardening.\n2.\nFind out the practices or techniques that make organic gardening unique fromother types of gardening.\n3.\nFind out the reasons why organic gardening is being practised.\n4.\nShare your findings with the class.\nExploring organic gardening practices\nActivity 2\nLet us do (in groups)\n1.\nWith the guidance of your teacher, pay a visit to a farm or a nearby agriculturalinstitution where organic gardening is practised.\n2.\nIdentify the crops which are grown in the farm.\nFOOD PRODUCTION PROCESSES"}, {"page": 24, "text": "3.\nFind out the following information:\na.\nHow soil fertility is improved to ensure proper growth of crops.\nb.\nMaterials or resources used to improve soil fertility.\nc.\nHow crop pests and diseases are controlled.\nd.\nHow weeds are controlled.\ne.\nOther gardening practices used to ensure healthy soil as well as safety ofcrop produce to humans and the environment.\nf.\nThe benefits of practising organic gardening.\nNote:\nYou may also seek the information from a resource person.\net us\nLean\nLr\nIn organic gardening, natural inputs such as organic manures, organic foliar feeds andnatural pesticides (bio-pesticides) are used instead of synthetic (chemical) fertilizers andpesticides. Cultural practices are used to ensure good environment for crop growth.\nExamples of cultural practices include selecting pest and disease resistant crops, use ofclean seeds, crop rotation, intercropping, cover cropping, mulching, non-chemical weedcontrol, use of trap crops to control pests, proper disposal of diseased crop residuesand good sanitation in the gardens. The principal behind organic gardening is to buildhealthy soil that ensures healthy crops so that they can resist pests and diseases.\nOrganic gardening promotes human health and food safety and also conserves theenvironment (water, soil and animals including beneficial insects and wildlife).\nEstablishing crops using organic techniques\nHow can we grow food crops through organic gardening? We will prepare a plantingsite, plant a crop and manage it using organic gardening techniques.\nActivity 3\nLet us talk (in groups)\n1.\nIdentify a short season crop (a vegetable, legume or spice) that is best suitedto grow in your environment. Some of the vegetables that you may grow arekales, spinach, cabbages, tomatoes, among others. Examples of legumes includecommon dry beans, garden peas, snow peas, French beans, groundnuts, greengrams, cowpeas and pigeon peas. Examples of spices include coriander, chillies,\noregano, basil, mint, ginger and rosemary. Consider factors such as availabilityof planting materials, suitability to the local climate, type of soil as well as pestand disease resistance. You can consult your teacher, parent or guardian andcrop production experts in the community."}, {"page": 25, "text": "2.\nPresent to the rest of the class, giving reasons why the crop you have chosenshould be adopted.\n3.\nAfter presentations, agree on the crop to be grown by the entire class.\nActivity 4\nLet us go digital\n1.\nDownload a video clip explaining how to grow the crop that you chose during\nActivity 3. You may use these search words: \nvideo on organic gardening of\n.\n(Insert the name of a crop that you intend to grow in the blank spaces).\nExample:\nVideo on organic gardening of common beans.\n2.\nYou may also search for more information from the internet, books and magazines.\n3.\nNote the cultural practices which are applied when growing the crop.\nPreparing a seedbed\nActivity 5\nLet us talk (in pairs)\n1.\nWhy should a seedbed be prepared before planting crops?\n2.\nWhat are the characteristics of a good site for preparing a seedbed?\n3.\nHow do we prepare a seedbed when practising organic gardening?\n4.\nThe pictures below show various types of seedbeds that may be used for growingcrops.\nFlat seed beds\nRaised seed beds\nSunken seedbeds\nRaised moisture bedc\nda\nbd\nab\nc"}, {"page": 26, "text": "Container garden\nMulti-story or conical gardens\nSuspended gardensa)\nDiscuss the conditions under which each of the above seedbeds is prepared.\nb)\nDiscuss how each of the above seedbeds is prepared.\nc)\nIn what ways can soil fertility in the seedbed be improved?\n5. Share with the rest of the class.\net us\nLean\nLr\nThe best planting site should be selected in order to grow healthy crops. The plantingsite should be fertile, well drained and free from chemical contamination. It should alsoreceive adequate sunlight. A seedbed is prepared to remove weeds and loosen the soilto ensure proper soil aeration, easy planting and water infiltration. Turning soil helpsto destroy various stages of pests by exposing them to the sun or birds. Any infectedplant remains should also be removed from the seedbed and destroyed.\nIn organic gardening, well rotten organic manures should be incorporated into the soilduring seedbed preparation. The organic manures should always be ready during thetime of seedbed preparation and planting. In the absence of compost or farm yardmanure, green manure can also be used to improve soil fertility. Leguminous plantsare planted on a seedbed and when they reach flowering stage, they are ploughedinto the soil so that they can decompose to release nutrients. An example of a greenmanuring plant is Mexican sunflower\n(tithonia)\n.\nef\nge\nfg"}, {"page": 27, "text": ".FYJDBO\u0001TVOnPXFS\u0001 UJUIPOJB\nIn case drainage is poor, the seedbed can be raised to prevent crop diseases especiallythose that affect roots. In places where drainage is good and rainfall is adequate,\nat seedbeds are suitable. However, in dry areas, water retention seedbeds such assunken seedbeds and shallow pits (Zai pits) can be prepared. In case there is shortageof space, innovative container gardening such as multi-storey gardens and suspendedgardens may be used.\nActivity 6\nLet us do (in groups)\n1.\nIdentify a suitable planting site in your school compound.\n2.\nAgree on the type of seedbed or seedbeds for establishing your preferred cropor crops.\n3.\nWrite down the tools and equipment as well as other materials that you willrequire for preparing your seedbed.\n4.\nUse the tools, equipment and other materials that you have identified to preparea suitable seedbed for raising the crop or crops chosen. In case seedlings requireto be raised in a nursery bed, prepare the nursery bed first, establish the seedlingsand take care until they are ready for transplanting to the seedbed.\nEnsure you mix the soil with well decomposed compost manure. You may also usefarm yard manure from cattle, sheep, goats, pigs, rabbits or poultry."}, {"page": 28, "text": "Note\nObserve safety when using the tools to avoid injuries.\nClean your tools and equipment after preparing your seedbed.\nPlanting a crop\nActivity 7\nLet us do (in groups)\n1.\nLook for suitable planting materials such as seeds, seedlings, tubers, and cuttingsfor the selected crop and bring them to the class. Your teacher may also assistin providing the planting materials.\n2.\nEnsure the planting materials selected are of high quality. How can you tell thatthe seeds or seedlings are of high quality?\n3.\nPlant the selected crop on a moist seedbed. Ask your teacher the number ofseeds to plant per hole, the depth of planting holes and the spacing of the holesbetween the rows and within the rows.\n4PXJOH\u0001TFFET\u0001JO\u0001B\u0001TVOLFO\u0001TFFECFE\n4PXJOH\u0001TFFET\u0001JO\u0001DPOUBJOFS\u0001TFFECFETa\nba\nb"}, {"page": 29, "text": "et us\nLean\nLr\nSeeds for planting should be wholesome, clean, dry and pest and disease free. Theseeds or other planting materials should be obtained from healthy and disease resistantcrops so that they tolerate the effects of pests and diseases. The selected plantingmaterials should also be suited to the climate and soil of a given place for bettersurvival and high yields. For example, sorghum, cassava, green grams, cowpeas andpigeon peas grow well in semi-arid areas because they are drought resistant. Thisis unlike green peas, potatoes and cabbages which do well in cool and moist areas.\nGrowing crops that are not well adapted to the environment will lead to higherchances of attack by pests and diseases. This leads to produce of low quality andquantity. Proper planting depth will enable seeds to germinate with ease. On theother hand, proper spacing ensures that the crops receive adequate nutrients, water,\nsunlight and air for proper growth.\n)PX\u0001UP\u0001TQBDF\u0001QJHFPO\u0001QFBT\nCare for the growing crop\nOnce the planting materials are planted, they require care for them to grow well.\nMaintaining crop nutrients and managing pests and diseases are key in organic farming.\nWe will therefore learn how to prepare organic fertilizers and pesticides. We shall thenapply the knowledge and skills learnt to take care of our crops. We will also carry outother cultural practices on the growing crops."}, {"page": 30, "text": "Activity 8\nLet us talk (in pairs)\n1.\nWhat cultural practices should be carried out on your growing crop?\n2.\nAt what stage of crop growth is each of the cultural practices done?\n3.\nWhy is each of the cultural practices important?\n4.\nHow are organic foliar feeds or fertilizers prepared?\n5.\nHow are organic pesticides prepared?\n6.\nApart from using organic pesticides, how else are pests and diseases controlledorganically?\n7.\nShare with the rest of the class.\nMaking foliar feed or fertilizer\nIt is important to top dress the growing crops with organic foliar feed. Top dressingis done when the crop has developed adequate roots and leaves so as to absorb thenutrients in the foliar feed or fertilizer. We will learn how to prepare foliar feeds usingorganic manures or soft plant materials.\nActivity 9\nLet us do (in groups)\n1.\nPut some compost in an empty 20 litre bucket. The compost should fill abouta third of the bucket.\n2.\nAdd clean fresh water to fill the bucket and stir thoroughly with a stake to makea solution as shown below.\n3.\nPut a lid on the bucket and place it in a well sheltered place for a few days.\n4.\nPour the solution through a piece of cloth into another bucket to remove thesolid matter."}, {"page": 31, "text": "'JMUFSJOH\u0001DPNQPTU\u000eXBUFS\u0001NJYUVSF\n5.\nAdd fresh clean water to the liquid manure collected in the bucket to dilute it. Thevolume of water should be twice that of the liquid manure. Your liquid manure,\nalso known as compost tea is now ready for application on your growing crop.\n\"QQMZJOH\u0001MJRVJE\u0001NBOVSF\u0001UP\u0001B\u0001DSPQ\nNote\nYou may use farm yard manure from chicken, pigs, cattle, sheep, goats and rabbitsto make liquid manure if compost manure is not available.\nAn alternative method of making liquid manure is to suspend a sack of manure insidea drum containing clean water for 7 days. Nutrients will be released slowly into thewater. The liquid manure should be diluted with water before applying to the crops.\nRabbit urine has also been found to be a good foliar feed (bio fertilizer). However, itshould be diluted with water in a ratio of 1:2 to avoid scorching the crops."}, {"page": 32, "text": "Activity 10\nLet us do (in groups)\n1.\nObtain soft sappy material (leaves and stems) from a leguminous plant such as\nMexican sunflower.\n2.\nChop it into small pieces.\n3.\nAdd the material into a bucket or drum with clean water. The ratio betweenthe material and the water may be 1:4.\n4.\nCover the bucket and leave for about 7 days to allow nutrients to be releasedinto the water as the plant material breaks down.\n5.\nDilute the foliar feed with water at a ratio of 1:10.\nWhat plant materials can you use to make foliar feed or fertilizer? Enquire from yourteacher and also search from the internet.\nMaking natural pesticides\nNatural pesticides are environmental friendly when compared to synthetic pesticides.\nThe aim is to repel pests so as to keep them away from the crops. We will preparesome natural pesticides (bio pesticides) using locally available materials to control pestsand some diseases in our growing crops. The best time to spray is early in the morningor the evening. This helps to avoid disintegration from the sun and to minimise harmto predators and beneficial insects such as bees\n.\nA few methods of preparing naturalpesticides are provided below.\nUsing ash brew\nThe alkaline nature of ash may deter some pests that attack crops. Ash from burntorganic materials such as wood or plant residues is mixed thoroughly with clean waterin a ratio of 1:10 in a clean container such as a bucket or drum. This means that forevery cup of ash, 10 cups of water are used. The mixture is left to soak for a few daysor a week depending on the type of material used to make the ash (soft or hard). Barsoap is grated into small pieces and then added into the mixture. The ratio of the soapto ash should be 1:10. The new mixture is then boiled while stirring for about 30 minutesto enhance melting of the soap. The mixture should then be allowed to cool for 1 to\n2 hours. After the ash has settled, the liquid (ash brew) should be poured into anothercontainer leaving the settled ash behind. Any remaining ash particles can be filtered outusing a fine mesh strainer or cheese cloth. The natural pesticide can be sprayed on theleaves, stems and surrounding soil around the crop where pests have been noticed. Itmay be reapplied after rain or when its effectiveness decreases."}, {"page": 33, "text": "Precautions\nAsh containing harmful chemicals should not be used. For example, ash from plasticmaterials and wood which has been treated and painted.\nAsh should not be allowed into the spray bottle or knapsack sprayer as it can clogthe nozzle.\nOne should wear protective gear such as gloves and safety googles when handlingthe ash or the ash brew.\nBefore spraying all the crops, one should spray a small area to ensure that the cropscan tolerate the ash brew.\nUsing hot pepper\n500 grams of hot pepper fruits are crushed and then mixed with 5 litres of water. Themixture is boiled for 20 minutes and allowed to cool. After sieving the mixture, 5 litres ofwater mixed with bar soap is added to the filtrate. The pesticide can be used to controlants, aphids, flies and caterpillars.\nUsing garlic\n10 to 12 cloves of crushed garlic are mixed with 1 litre of water. After settling for 24\nhours, the mixture is strained using a piece of cloth. A cup of cooking oil is then addedto the filtrate and then sprayed on the crop. A mixture of garlic, onion and water canalso be used as a pesticide. The strong smell of the spray repels the pests away fromthe crops.\nUsing pyrethrum spray\n20g pyrethrum powder is mixed with 10 litres water. Soap may be added to enhancelong lasting effects. The mixture is then strained and applied immediately on the pests.\nIn addition, dry pyrethrum flowers may be ground into powder and then dusted overinsect pests.\nUsing baking soda spray\nFour teaspoons of baking soda are mixed in one litre of water. The mixture is added to twotablespoons of vegetable oil and two tablespoons of liquid soap and shaken vigorously.\nMilk spray\nOne litre of milk is mixed with one litre of water and then sprayed to control mildew, afungal disease in some vegetable crops.\nUsing Sodom apple and Mexican marigold\nFruits of Sodom apple and Mexican marigold leaves are crushed and then soaked inwater for 2 weeks. Some liquid soap may be added to assist the mixture to stick on thecrops. The pesticide is used to repel aphids and other pests."}, {"page": 34, "text": "Note\nIt is good to try what works best since there is no recommended amount of pesticideto apply unlike when using synthetic chemicals. Other natural pesticides include rabbiturine, neem oil, tobacco spray, tomato and black nightshade spray and wood ash.\nYou may find out how such homemade pesticides are used to control crop pests inthe garden. In addition, there are safe bio-pesticides being sold in the market.\nOther ways of managing pests and diseases in crops\nField hygiene or sanitation\nSeriously infected plants should be uprooted and destroyed to prevent spreading pestsand diseases. This practice is called\nSPHVJOH\u000f\nIn addition, clean tools and equipment shouldbe used in the garden to avoid introducing diseases in the garden.\nFlooding and irrigation\nFlooding minimises pests which hide in the soil, for example, cutworms. Overhead irrigationcan help to dislodge aphids from the leaves and drown spider mites. However, the twomethods should target the specific pests since they can bring more problems. For example,\nooding soil can affect respiration of crop roots and also lead to soil erosion. Overheadirrigation, on the other hand, can increase chances of diseases that affect the crop leaves.\nNatural predators\nIt is important to encourage natural predators of pests in the garden. For example,\nchameleons, ladybird beetles, spiders, green lacewings, parasitic wasps and praying mantiseat various insect pests that attack crops. It is important to have a variety of plants thatprovide habitat for such beneficial organisms in an organic garden.\nCrop rotation\nCrops which are related should be planted in a rotation program because they areattacked by similar pests and diseases. For example, tomatoes should not be plantedin a site where potatoes, eggplant and chillies had been planted. Similarly, watermelonshould not be planted where cucumber, pumpkin or butternut had been planted in theprevious season.\nCompanion planting\nThis refers to close planting of different plants to enhance each others growth and protectthem from pests. For example, vegetables can be planted together with some herbs suchas basil, mint and rosemary which serve as pest repellents. Carrots and onions are alsogood companion crops for repelling onion flies and carrot flies respectively."}, {"page": 35, "text": "Weed control\nSome weeds harbour a number of pests and disease-causing organisms (fungi, bacteriaand viruses) which can easily spread to the crops. Therefore, non-chemical methods ofweed control such as mulching, uprooting weeds and tilling land are recommended tosuppress weed growth. It is important to avoid tilling land when soil is too wet or whenit is raining because diseases can spread fast under such conditions.\nActivity 11\nLet us do (in groups)\n1.\nMonitor your growing crop regularly throughout the growing season. Carryout appropriate cultural practices on your growing crops. Inform your teacherimmediately you notice any unusual appearance on your crop. In case pests arefew, hand pick them and destroy them. Your teacher will guide you more onhow to deal with pests and diseases in case they appear on your growing crop.\n2.\nShare responsibilities among the members of the group using a duty schedulelike the one shown below.\nSample project duty schedule\nGroup A\nName of crop:\nFrench beans\nName of group leader\n: Peter Musyoka\nDate\nCultural practice\nResponsibilityallocated to\nRemarks by the teacher\nGapping\nSheilla, Hassan,\nDanson, Mary\nWell done.\nThinning\nAbdi, Otieno,\nHilda, christine\nNot yet completed.\nMembers were reminded tothin excess seedlings.\nMulching\nIrrigation (watering)\nMechanical weeding\nTop dressing (usingorganic foliar feedsor manures)\nPest and diseasecontrol by culturalmethods (specify)\nOthers (specify)"}, {"page": 36, "text": "Note\nYou may take photographs as you carry out the various gardening practices on yourcrop. Save the photographs in your portfolio for assessment by your teacher. Ensurethe photographs have dates to show when the gardening practices were done. Youmay also keep a journal to record your gardening activities as well as any successesand challenges experienced.\nHarvesting of crops\nOrganically grown crops, just like other crops should be harvested at the appropriatestage of maturity in order to get maximum benefit and minimise field losses.\nActivity 12\nLet us go digital\nWe will learn how to harvest crops.\n1.\nUse digital devices find out the following information:\na)\nThe right stage of harvesting vegetables, legumes and spices.\nb)\nThe part of the vegetable, legume and spice that is harvested.\nc)\nHow the various vegetables, legumes and spices are harvested.\nd)\nThe precautions that should be observed when harvesting the crops.\nNote\nIn each category pick any two crops that you are familiar with. Ensure you includethe crop that you have grown in your garden. You may observe videos on how suchcrops are harvested. Where digital devices are not available contact a resource personto explain how harvesting is done."}, {"page": 37, "text": "2.Summarise your findings in a table like the one shown below.\nName ofcrop\nPartthat isharvested\nRight stageof harvesting\n(signsindicatingharvestreadiness)\nHow the crop isharvested\nPrecautions toobserve whileharvesting\nSpinach\nLeaves\nWhen spinachhave large,\nfresh, tenderand dark greenmature leaves.\nThis will beafter 2  3\nmonths afterplanting.\nUsing a thumb andforefinger, pinch offthe large outer leavesclose to the base ofthe plant, but justabove the top of thesoil level. You canalso use a knife orpair of scissors to cutoff the stems.\n\nAllow the innerleaves to grow.\n\nAfter harvesting,\nremove old yellowor brown leavesfrom the bunch anddiscard them.\n\nHarvesting can bedone one or twotimes in a weekuntil the cop stopsgrowing.\nKale\nLeaves\nAfter about\n6 weeks fromthe time oftransplanting.\nCheck for kalethat has firm,\ndeeply colouredleaves andmoist hardystems.\nUsing hands, knifeor scissors, pluck thelower large leavesrst and then workyour way up theplant. Harvesting canbe done for 4 to 6\nmonths depending onthe care given to thecrop.\n\n3 to 4 top leavesshould not beharvested.\n\nA small part of thestalk (about 2.5\ncm) should be leftattached to avoiddamaging the stem.\n\nAvoid picking theterminal bud whichis the top centreof the plant tomaintain the cropsproductivity.\nDry beans\nPods\nWhen most ofthe pods aredry and turnbrown. Theseeds inside thepod should behard.\nBy pulling thewhole plant byhand. The drypods are threshed.\nThis is followed bywinnowing, thensorting in order tohave clean seeds.\n\nHarvesting shouldbe done in themorning and whenweather is dry."}, {"page": 38, "text": "Groundnuts\nPods\nWhen seeds inthe pods arebig enough toll the pods.\nWhen the podsare pressed byngers, theysplit easily.\nWhole plant is liftedfrom the groundto obtain the podsbecause they areunderground. Theyare allowed to dryin the sun for a fewdays, then shelledto remove the seeds.\nWinnowing andsorting are then doneto obtain clean seeds.\n\nWhen the weatheris dry to preventrotting of seeds.\nCoriander\n(Dhania)\nLeaves\nAfter about\n4 to 6 weeksafter planting.\nWhole plants withleaves are uprootedor cut at the base.\n\nWhen leaves arebig and still greennot feathery oryellow.\n\nLarge plants shouldbe harvested firstto allow the growthof the small plants.\n)BSWFTUJOH\u0001PG\u0001LBMF\n)BSWFTUJOH\u0001PG\u0001DBSSPUT\n)BSWFTUJOH\u0001PG\u0001TXFFU\u0001QFQQFS\n6QSPPUJOH\u0001NBUVSF\u0001ESZ\u0001CFBOTd\nab\nca\nbc\nd"}, {"page": 39, "text": "6QSPPUJOH\u0001HSPVOEOVUT\u0001CZ\u0001IBOE\nActivity 13\nLet us do (in groups)\n1.\nUsing the knowledge and skills acquired, harvest your crop once it is ready.\nObserve hygiene and ensure you handle your harvested crop especially thevegetables and spices with care to avoid causing injuries and bruises.\n2.\nYour teacher will guide you on what to do with the harvested crop produce.\nImportance of organic gardening\nWe will create educative messages on the benefits of organic gardening.\nActivity 14\nLet us do (in groups)\nPrepare creative messages that you will use to sensitise your community on the healthbenefits of eating organically grown foods.\nDisplay such messages in appropriate places in the school. See a sample poster below.\nee"}, {"page": 40, "text": "et us\nLean\nLr\nSome of the benefits of organic gardening include:\na)\nWe avoid harmful chemicals that can harm the growers, consumers and animalsincluding beneficial insects in the environment. The organic pesticides used haveshort residue effect and decay easily when compared to synthetic pesticides.\nb)\nIt is cheaper since we save on costs of buying the synthetic chemicals.\nc)\nHelps in environmental conservation, for example when natural wastes areconverted into manure.\nd)\nHelps to improve soil quality. The organic manure supplies nutrients not only tothe crops but also to useful soil organisms such as earthworms, some fungi andsome bacteria which help in decomposing organic wastes. In addition, organicmanure enables the soil to hold enough moisture for crop growth.\ne)\nFarmers can access export markets in countries where demand for organicproducts is high as long as they adhere to the required standards.\nHowever, organic farming requires high labour and more time compared to conventionalgardening.\nAssess yourself\n1.\nWhich of the following would an organic gardenernotuse when growing crops?\nA)\nCompost manure.\nB)\nPoultry droppings.\nC)\nArtificial fertilizer.\nD)\nOrganic mulch.\n2.\nIn a text box next to each sentence, place a\nT\nif the statement is\nTRUEandan\nF\nif the statement is\nFALSEas demonstrated in the first statement below.\na)\nSoil and water conservation measures are important in organic gardening.\nb)\nMost crops grow well on waterlogged soils.\nc)\nMixing organic manure with soil makes the soil more permeable towater.\nd)\nOrganically grown crops are safe to eat because they do not havechemical residues.\ne)\nUsing clean tools while working in a garden can prevent the spread ofdiseases on crops.\nf)\nMouldy, wet and broken seeds can be selected for sowing.\ng)\nLegume crops such as beans and peas that are intended for storageas dry grains are harvested when the pods are small and have greencolour."}, {"page": 41, "text": "h)\nSunken beds can be used for raising some crops in dry areas.\ni)\nRegular monitoring of the growing crops is necessary to check presenceof weeds, pests and diseases.\nj)\nThinning increases the number of crop plants in a garden.\n3.\nChoose the best option in the brackets.\na)\nOrganically grown legumes are safe and healthy to eat.\n[true or false].\nb)\nUse of agricultural chemicals is discouraged because if proper precautionsare not observed, beneficial organisms are killed.\n[true or false].\nc)\nIf domestic animals eat remains of crops that have residues of agriculturalchemicals, nothing will happen to our health.\n[true or false].\nd)\nWhen people consume food which contains residues of chemicals thatwere sprayed on the crop, they can\n[become sick; become healed].\ne)\nCases of several incidences of pest attack is an indication of\n[goodhealth of the soil and crops\n,\npoor health of the soil and crop]\n.\nf)\nOrganically grown crops do not attract insect pests because they have\n[soft and succulent stems, hard stems]\ng)\nOverhead irrigation in some crops such as tomatoes\n[increases spreadof diseases\n,\nreduces spread of diseases]\n4.\nA Grade 9 learner heard some farmers complaining that artificial fertilizers andpesticides are becoming increasingly expensive.\na)\nWhat can the farmers use in the absence of artificial fertilizers?\nb)\nApart from cost, give two other disadvantages of using artificial fertilizersin a garden.\nc)\nDescribe how a farmer can prepare a natural pesticide to reduce thecost of production.\n5.\nFarmers in your community are interested in organic gardening. Give any sixorganic gardening practices that they may carry out on their gardens."}, {"page": 42, "text": "Storage of Crop Produce\nCrop produce gets spoilt if it is not stored appropriately. Poor storage of crop produce canalso lead to contamination of the produce making it unhealthy for human consumption.\nTherefore, it is important to prepare the storage produce to ensure we have healthyfoods. Which facilities are used to store crop produce in our school and homes? Howcan we prepare the facilities where we store foods in our schools and homes?\nCrop storage structures\nCrop produce include grains, cereals and tubers that are either bought or harvested fromour gardens. Before storing the crop produce, we should prepare the facilities where westore the crop produce. Jumas family grows maize. They harvest the maize and storeit in a granary. Hamisis guardians grow groundnuts. They harvest them, dry them andstore them in a big jar.\n5SBEJUJPOBM\u0001HSBOBSZ\n%SVN\u0001PS\u0001QMBTUJD\u0001KBS\nActivity 1\nLet us talk (in pairs)\n1.\nWhich structures do you use to store crop produce at home or school?\nOther facilities that can be used to store crop produce include modern granaries, storerooms, storage bags and small containers such as plastic or glass jars and earthen pots.\nab\nab"}, {"page": 43, "text": "Ways of preparing storage structures for crop produce\nActivity 2\nLet us talk (in pairs)\n1.\nHow can you prepare the storage of crop produce at home or school?\n2.\nHow can we prepare the storage structures shown in the following picturesbefore storing crop produce?\n.PEFSO\u0001HSBOBSZ\n1FTU\u0001QSPPG\u0001TUPSBHF\u0001CBHT\n4UPSBHF\u0001DPOUBJOFSTa\nbc\nab\nc"}, {"page": 44, "text": "Before storing the crop produce in the storage structures and facilities, they should beprepared to ensure that they are safe to handle crop produce. Storage facilities andstructures should keep the produce free from water to avoid rotting, free from dust toavoid contamination and secure from pests such as rats and weevils.\nJumas family prepares the granary in the following ways before storing maize:\n1.\nThey clean the granary to remove wastes from the previous crop remains.\n2.\nThey seal all the openings where rainwater can pass through.\n3.\nThey clean and dry the storage bags.\n4.\nThey dust the granary with some pesticide to kill any weevils and pests in thegranary.\nHamisis guardian prepares the grain storage container by:\n1.\nCleaning the container to remove any remains from previous crop produce.\n2.\nDrying the container to ensure it has no wet parts.\n3.\nCleaning the lid and ensuring it is tightly fitting to prevent entry of pests.\nPreparation of a storage facility or structure for storingcrop produce\nPreparation of a structure or facility for storing crop produce should be done to ensurethat the produce is stored in a safe place away from contamination. It also maintainsthe quality of the stored crop produce.\nActivity 3\nPreparing a storage facility or structure forstoring crop produce\nUse the ideas you have gained from your previous discussion to prepare a storagestructure or facility in readiness for storing crop produce. At home, seek guidance ofyour parents or guardians. While at school, you will be guided by your teacher toprepare the store where cereals and pulses are stored. Prepare the storage structureor facility by carrying out the following:\n1.\nRemoving all the remains of the previous crop produce.\n2.\nSweeping or cleaning the storage room.\n3.\nRemoving any form of dust, dirt, remains of previous content of the storagecontainers, bad smell and unpleasant odours.\n4.\nOpening the room or structure to allow fresh air circulation.\n5.\nSealing parts such as the roof of the granary to prevent leaking.\n6.\nReplacing any broken parts such as the rodent guards for the granary.\n7.\nDusting the store room or granary to kill any pests."}, {"page": 45, "text": "Managing stored crop produce to reduce spoilage\nStored crop produce should be handled appropriately while in the storage facilities andstructures to ensure that they remain in good condition. Poor handling of the producecan lead to rotting and contamination of the produce.\nActivity 4\nLet us do (in groups)\n1.\nHow can you care for the crop produce in your storage facilities at home?\n2.\nHow can you care for the crop produce in the storage room at school?\n3.\nHow can we be responsible in managing our stored crop produce? Your teacherwill guide you on how to check the storage room in school and carry out anynecessary practices to prevent spoilage of the stored crop produce. You canpractise the learnt skills at home.\net us\nLean\nLr\nThe following are some practices that are carried out in a storage store or facility toreduce spoilage of crop produce:\n1.\nCheck the storage room and containers to ensure they are always dry with nosigns of wetness and exposure to cold weather.\n2.\nEnsure the storage room is always cool and dry\n3.\nUse dry container to fetch the grains from the storage sacks.\n4.\nCheck to ensure that there is adequate air circulation in the storage room. Thiscontrols dampness and accumulation of bad odours.\n5.\nCheck to remove any contamination or spoilt produce that may lead to growthof moulds in the storage facility.\n6.\nCheck and remove any crop produce that has signs of pests, diseases or spoilageto prevent spread.\n7.\nAvoid returning partially cut crop produce such as fruits, cabbages and pumpkinsto the storage facility.\n8.\nClearing vegetation around the store room or granary.\n9.\nMaintain the storage facility in clean condition.\nProper storage of crop produce reduces food spoilage to ensure that we have foodat all times. Therefore, it enhances food security."}, {"page": 46, "text": "Assess yourself\n1.\nWhy should the storage facility be kept dry?\n2.\nList three causes of wetness in a storage facility.\n3.\nExplain how you can reduce bad odours in a granary.\n4.\nJamila bought a plastic drum for storing her grains. Explain how she can preparethe drum before storing the grains.\n5.\nHamisi found some rotten grains in the sack while fetching maize for cooking.\nWhat should he do to ensure food safety of the stored maize?\n6.\nJane wanted to keep their granary clean. Her mother told her to sweep thegranary. Why did her mother advise her to sweep the granary and not mop itwith water?\n7.\nList the caring practices you would carry out to ensure grains stored in yourschool store are safe."}, {"page": 47, "text": "Cooking: Using Flour Mixtures\nFlour mixtures are a combination of wheat flour, raising agents and other ingredientssuch as fat, salt, sugar and liquid (milk, eggs, orange juice or water).\nTypes of flour mixtures\nFlour can be mixed in different ways to get a range of products. The types of flourmixtures also range from the proportion of flour and other ingredients used.\nActivity 1\nLet us go digital\n1.\nIdentify the types of flour mixtures shown in the pictures below.\n2.\nUse print or digital resources to find the definitions of the following terms inrelation to flour mixtures:\na)\nDough.\nb)\nBatter.\n3.\nPresent your findings in class.\nThe following are the types of flour mixtures:\na)\nBatter: This flour mixture has a flowing consistency. There are two types ofbatter: thick batter and thin batter.\nb)\nDough: This flour mixture is soft but firm. It is also elastic and can be kneadedor rolled.\nab\nab"}, {"page": 48, "text": "Preparing flour mixtures\nActivity 2\nLet us do (in groups)\nWith the guidance of your teacher, prepare batter.\nRequirements\n2 cups of flour, 1 egg, 2 cups of water, salt, hand whisk or spoon, cup and a basinor bowl.\nWhat to do\n1.\nSieve the flour and salt in a bowl or basin and make a hole in the centreof the flour.\n2.\nBreak the egg in a cup and beat it lightly.\n3.\nPour in the beaten egg with a little water. Beat the mixture until the batterbecomes smooth. Add water as necessary to create the desired consistencyof batter.\n4.\nCover and leave it to stand.\n5.\nUse the batter as required."}, {"page": 49, "text": "Activity 3\nLet us do (in groups)\nWith the guidance of your teacher, prepare dough.\nRequirements\n250 grams flour, 100 grams of margarine or cooking oil or fat, 150 milligrams ofmilk or water and salt.\nWhat to do\n1.\nSift flour, sugar and salt together.\n2.\nAdd margarine or fat to the flour and rub it in.\n3.\nAdd the milk or water and knead to produce dough.\n4.\nPut the dough aside, cover it with a dry cloth and leave it to stand for thirtyminutes.\n5.\nKnead the dough again.\n6.\nRoll out the dough and shape as desired.\nMaking products from various flour mixtures\nActivity 4\nLet us talk (in pairs)\nHow can we make products from flour mixtures?\nActivity 5\nLet us talk (in pairs)\n1.\nIdentify the products shown in the following pictures.\nba\nab"}, {"page": 50, "text": "2.\nWhich flour mixtures have been used to make the products shown in pictures\n(a) to (d)?\n3.\nList other products made using batter and dough.\n4.\nShare your ideas in class.\net us\nLean\nLr\n1.\nWe can make products from flour mixtures by shallow frying, baking and deepfrying.\n2.\nDough is used to make\nDIBQBUJ\n,\nNBOEB[J\n,\nNBIBNSJ\n, doughnuts and bread.\n3.\nThin batter is used to make pancakes.\n4.\nThick batter is used for coating foods such as fish, chicken and potatoes (\nWJB[J\u0001\nLBSBJ\n). It can also be used to make drop scones.\nActivity 6\nLet us do (in groups)\nWith the guidance of your teacher, prepare pancakes.\nWhat to do\n1.\nUse the recipe for making batter provided in (\nActivity 2, page 48\n).\n2.\nHeat a little amount of cooking oil in the frying pan.\n3.\nPour the batter to cover the base of the pan thinly and cook until browned.\ncd\ncd"}, {"page": 51, "text": "4.\nFlip the pancake over when bubbles start to form on the surface.\n5.\nCook the other side until browned.\n6.\nPlace the pancake on the plate.\n7.\nCook all pancakes. Serve hot on a clean plate.\nActivity 7\nLet us do (in groups)\nWith the guidance of your teacher, prepare\nDIBQBUJ\n.\nRequirements\n250 grams flour, basin or bowl, knife, cooking oil, warm water, salt, shallow fryingpan, basting brush or spoon, fish slice, rolling pin and rolling board.\nWhat to do\n1.\nUse the recipe for making dough provided in (\nActivity 3, page 49)\n.\nRoll the dough on a lightly floured rolling board and lightly brush the rolled outdough with some oil."}, {"page": 52, "text": "2.\nCut the rolled\nDIBQBUJdough into strips and roll them into a spiral shape to thedesired size. Repeat this process to the rest of the strips.\n3.\nLightly flour the rolling board and roll out each of the balls of coiled dough toform a circular shape.\n4.\nPreheat a pan and place the\nDIBQBUJdough to cook for about one minute.\n5.\nFlip the\nDIBQBUJand allow the other side to cook for one minute. Brush the topsurface with little oil.\n6.\nFlip the\nDIBQBUJover and let it cook until you achieve your desired brownness.\nSmear the top dry part with a little oil then flip to cook to the desired brownness.\n7.\nRepeat procedure three to six with the rest of the coiled shaped dough balls."}, {"page": 53, "text": "Activity 8\nLet us do (in groups)\nWith the guidance of your teacher, prepare\nNBOEB[J\n.\nRequirements\n250 grams self raising flour, margarine, basin or bowl, an egg, cooking oil, warm wateror milk, knife, sugar, deep frying pan, slotted spoon, rolling pin and rolling board.\nWhat to do\n1.\nUse the recipe for making dough provided in\n(\nActivity 3, page 49)\n.\n2.\nRoll the dough on a lightly floured rolling board.\n3.\nUsing a knife, cut out the rolled dough into the desired shapes.\n4.\nAdd cooking oil in the deep frying pan and place it on the source of heat. Thepan should not be more than two thirds full for safety.\n5.\nWhen the oil is hot enough, use a slotted spoon to gently lower the shapedpieces of dough into the hot oil to avoid the oil from splashing.\n6.\nFry the dough in hot oil until it browns.\n7.\nFlip the\nNBOEB[Jand fry the other side until brown.\n8.\nServe the\nNBOEB[Jon a clean plate."}, {"page": 54, "text": "Assess yourself\n1.\nWhich of the following statements are true regarding batter and dough?\na)\nBatter has high water content to flour.\nb)\nThere are two types of dough; thin dough and thick dough.\nc)\nFood items made using dough include pancakes.\nd)\nThick batter is used for coating foods.\n2.\nWhich food items can be prepared using:\na)\nBatter.\nb)\nDough.\n3.\nSolve the following riddles:\na)\nI am thin and can be poured with ease in a pan. Pancakes or drop scones,\nI am part of the plan. Who am I?\nb)\nI am soft and stretchy. Knead me well, let me rise. I can also be mouldedand shaped. Who am I?"}, {"page": 55, "text": "Hygiene refers to cleanliness. Hygiene practices involve various practices that promotehealth, cleanliness and well-being in our daily lives. From personal hygiene to householdsanitation practices, maintaining cleanliness is essential in creating a safe environmentfor us.\nCleaning Waste Disposal Facilities\nWaste disposal facilities refer to systems designed for the collection and disposal ofvarious types of waste generated by households. These facilities play a crucial role inproper management of waste.\nImportance of cleaning waste disposal facilities\nActivity 1\nLet us talk (in pairs)\nHow do you dispose waste at home?\nActivity 2\nLet us do (in groups)\n1.\nIdentify the waste disposal facilities shown in the following pictures.\nHYGIENE PRACTICESa\nbc"}, {"page": 56, "text": "2.\nTake a walk around your school.\na)\nIdentify the waste disposal facilities used in school.\nb)\nBrainstorm on the type of waste\n(liquid or solid)\neach disposal facility youidentifled handles.\n3.\nShare your ideas in class.\nActivity 3\nLet us do (in pairs)\nDavid, a Grade 9 learner, researched on the Internet for information on the variouswaste disposal facilities. He formulated riddles using his flndings. Read and solve eachriddle.\n1.\nI am a fixture commonly found in both kitchens and bathrooms.\nIn the kitchen, I am utilised to clean utensils. In the bathroom, Iserve the purpose of facilitating hand washing and other personalhygiene activities. What am I?\n2.\nI am a narrow ditch used to drain waste water from buildingsto main gutters. I am open at the surface, you can see as wastewater flows. What am I?\n3.\nI am a container with a crucial role. Preventing littering andkeeping the environment clean. In me, waste finds a temporarystay. Until proper disposal, I heed the call. What am I?\net us\nLean\nLr\n1.\nWaste bin: It is also known as a trash bin, garbage can or dustbin. It is acontainer speciflcally designed for the temporary storage and disposal of solidwaste. Waste bins hold waste until it can be properly disposed of.\n2.\nSink: This is a plumbing flxture that is flxed to the wall in a kitchen or bathroom.\nIt consists of a basin with a tap for supplying water and a drain for removingwaste water.\n3.\nOpen drains: They are narrow channels or ditches designed to drain wastewater or rain water away from buildings to main gutters by the roadsides. Themain gutters then carry waste water out of the town. Open drains range fromwell-constructed ones made from cement, metals or plastic to simple trenchesdug on the ground."}, {"page": 57, "text": "Activity 4\nLet us talk (in groups)\n1.\nWhat are the consequences of not cleaning waste disposal facilities as shownin the following picture?\n2.\nExplain the importance of cleaning waste disposal facilities.\n3.\nShare your experiences on the importance of cleaning waste disposal facilities.\n4.\nWrite down your ideas and present them in class.\net us\nLean\nLr\nImportance of cleaning waste disposal facilities\n1.\nKeeps away disease causing germs to ensure good health and well-being of thefamily members.\n2.\nCleaning sinks and drains prevents clogs and blockages. This ensures properow of waste water.\n3.\nRegular cleaning prevents bad odours.\n4.\nRegular maintenance and cleaning can extend the lifespan of waste disposalfacilities. This reduces the need for frequent repairs which helps to save money.\n5.\nClean waste disposal facilities contribute to comfortable and enjoyable livingconditions.\n6.\nTo prevent build-up of dirt which may be expensive to remove.\nActivity 5\nLet us do (in groups)\nWith the guidance of your teacher, use the following procedure to clean a waste bin.\nRequirements\nWaste bin, gloves, water, detergent, scrub brush or sponge, baking soda and trash bag."}, {"page": 58, "text": "Steps to follow\n1.\nCollect the materials and equipment required.\n2.\nWear the gloves to protect your hands from contact with waste.\n3.\nEmpty the waste bin.\n4.\nUse water to rinse the waste bin to remove loose dirt.\n5.\nFill a bucket with warm water and add the detergent.\n6.\nDip a sponge into the soapy water and scrub the interior and exterior of thewaste bin properly, paying attention to the corners and the bottom of the bin.\nIf there are odours or stains, sprinkle baking soda in the waste bin and let it sitfor ten minutes before scrubbing it again.\n7.\nRinse the waste bin with clean warm water to remove soap and dirt.\n8.\nRinse with cold water to which disinfectant has been added.\n9.\nLeave the bin to air dry thoroughly.\n10.\nClean, dry and store the tools, equipment and materials used for cleaning.\n11.\nOnce dry, line the waste bin ready for use."}, {"page": 59, "text": "Activity 6\nLet us do (in groups)\nWith the guidance of your teacher, use the following procedure to clean a sink.\nRequirements\nBaking soda, gloves scouring pad, soft clean cloth, clean toothbrush, hot water andvinegar.\nSteps to follow\n1.\nGather the necessary cleaning tools and materials.\n2.\nWear the gloves to protect your hands from contact with dirt.\n3.\nEmpty the sink and rinse it using clean water to remove loose dirt.\n4.\nSprinkle baking soda on the sink basin and let it sit for about 10 minutes.\n5.\nScrub the sink basin thoroughly. Clean the tap and under the sink using ascouring pad and warm soapy water.\n6.\nDip a clean toothbrush in the warm soapy water and use it to scrub the baseof the tap and the drain.\n7.\nRinse the sink using clean warm water followed by cold water.\n8.\nPour hot water mixed with vinegar down the drain to fiush down the dirt, unclogand kill germs.\n9.\nAllow cold water to run through the drain.\n10.\nDry the sink with a soft clean cloth."}, {"page": 60, "text": "Note\nA clogged sink can allow build-up of dirt since waste water is not able to drainproperly.\nIf necessary, use the following procedure to unclog the sink:\n1.\nFill the sink halfway with cold water.\n2.\nPosition a suction pump over the drain.\n3.\nWork the suction pump up and down quickly.\n4.\nRemove the suction pump from the drain opening and see if the water startsto drain.\n5.\nContinue using the suction pump until the clog is dislodged.\nActivity 7\nLet us do (in groups)\nWith the guidance of your teacher, use the following procedure to clean a cementedopen drain.\nRequirements\nWater, scrubbing brush, long stiff wire, detergent, bucket and disinfectant.\nSteps to follow\n1.\nCollect the materials and equipment required.\n2.\nWear the gloves to protect your hands from contact with dirt.\n3.\nCollect any litter or leaves from the drain so that waste water can fiow easily."}, {"page": 61, "text": "4.\nPour warm soapy water down the drain and scrub using a stiff bristle brush.\n5.\nUse clean warm water to rinse the drain.\n6.\nTo eliminate odours, sprinkle baking soda over the drain surface. Follow thisby pouring white vinegar over the baking soda.\n7.\nScrub using a brush. Flush the drain using clean hot water.\n8.\nRinse the drain using clean cold water.\nActivity 8\nLet us do (in groups)\nWith the guidance of your teacher, use the following procedure to clean an earthenopen drain.\n1.\nWear gloves to protect your hands from contact with dirt.\n2.\nCollect any litter or leaves from the drains so that waste water can fiow easily.\n3.\nPull out any weeds using your hands.\nTake home activity\n1.\nAssist your parent or guardian to clean waste disposal facilities at home.\n2.\nShare your experiences in class.\nActivity 9\nLet us do (in groups)\n1.\nDecide how often the class waste bin needs to be cleaned.\n2.\nCreate a duty roster where each learner is assigned a day to clean the classwaste bin.\n3.\nDisplay the duty roster in the classroom noticeboard.\n4.\nEnsure you all participate in cleaning the waste bin in order to create a healthylearning environment."}, {"page": 62, "text": "Activity 10\nLet us do (in pairs)\nGrade 9 learners are discussing some of the practices they will adopt to keep theirwaste disposal facilities clean. Read the presentations they made and answer thequestions that follow.\nRinse the sinkafter each use.\nClean water shouldbe poured through thedrains after use.\nUse waste bin liners andchange them regularly.\n1.\nWhat is the importance of pouring clean water through the drains after use?\n2.\nWhy is it recommended to rinse the sink after each use?\n3.\nWhat is the importance of lining waste bins?\nAssess yourself\n1.\nDiscuss the meaning of this statement:\nRegular cleaning is our flrst defence.\n2.\nRoman would like to assist his mother to clean their kitchen sink. However, thesink is clogged.\na)\nWhich procedure should he use to unclog the sink?\nb)\nWrite down the procedure he is likely to use to clean the sink."}, {"page": 63, "text": "Disinfecting Clothing And Household Articles\nDisinfecting is carried out to avoid the spread of communicable diseases from one personto another. Disinfecting reduces the chances of infection through clothing and householdarticles.\nMethods of disinfecting clothing and household articles\nDisinfection of clothing and household articles is important in maintaining cleanlinessand promoting health within our homes. Disinfection can be done in various ways.\nActivity 1\nLet us talk (in groups)\nShare experiences on methods of disinfecting clothing and household articles you useat home.\nActivity 2\nLet us do (in pairs)\nStudy the pictures below and answer the questions that follow.\n1.\nIdentify the methods of disinfecting clothing and household articles shown inpictures (a) and (b).\n2.\nDescribe other methods used to disinfect clothing and household articles.\n3.\nShare your ideas in class.\nab\nab"}, {"page": 64, "text": "Activity 3\nLet us do (individually)\nComplete the following crossword puzzle on the methods used to disinfect clothingand household articles.\nAcross\n2. This natural method uses UV rays to disinfect clothes when they are hung outdoors.\n3. Which method involves heating water to a high temperature to disinfect clothes?\n5. Which technique uses a common kitchen ingredient to help disinfect clothes?\nDown\n1. Chemical agents specially formulated to kill germs on clothes are known as?\n4. A laundry process that not only removes wrinkles but also aids in disinfectingclothes.\nHints\nDisinfectants, boiling, ironing, salting, sunlight"}, {"page": 65, "text": "et us\nLean\nLr\n1.\nBoiling: This involves putting clothes which have been thoroughly washed andrinsed into boiling water. The high temperature helps to kill bacteria and virusespresent in clothing and household articles.\n2.\nUse of disinfectants: These are chemical substances used to kill disease causinggerms.\n3.\nSunlight: Sunlight is a natural disinfectant. Hanging clothes under the sun helpsto kill virus and bacteria.\n4.\nSalting: This involves using table salt to soak clothes during the laundry process.\nThis helps to kill disease causing germs.\n5.\nIroning: This not only removes wrinkles from clothes but also disinfects. The heatgenerated by the iron helps to kill some microorganisms on the fabric.\nNote\nMethods of disinfecting clothing and household articles such as drying in the sun,\nsalting and using a hot iron may be used to kill germs. However, they may not beeffective by themselves. Therefore, you may consider using a combination of twomethods to enhance the effectiveness.\nDisinfecting clothing and household articles\nActivity 4\nLet us talk (in pairs)\nWhich fabrics can withstand boiling as a method of disinfecting?\nActivity 5\nLet us do (in groups)\nBoiling\nWith the guidance of your teacher, practice boiling as a method of disinfecting clothes.\nRequirements\nBasins, soap, water, pegs, white cotton kitchen towel, clean stick or tongs, sourceof heat andsufuria\n.\nWhat to do\n1.\nSoak the kitchen towel in cold water for about 20 minutes to loosen dirt."}, {"page": 66, "text": "2.\nWash the kitchen towel in warm soapy water using friction method.\n(refer tothe procedure of laundering a cotton item learnt in Grade 5).\n3.\nRinse the kitchen towel thoroughly to remove all traces of soap.\n4.\nPut the kitchen towel in boiling water for about ten minutes\n5.\nTurn the kitchen towel from time to time using a clean stick or tongs.\n6.\nRemove the kitchen towel from the boiling water. Make the flnal rinse in coldwater to freshen.\n7.\nDry the kitchen towel on a clothesline under the sun. Secure with pegs.\n8.\nAfter drying, fold the kitchen towel and store in a dry place.\nCaution\nObserve safety precautions while boiling to prevent burns and scalds.\net us\nLean\nLr\nBoiling is suitable for white cottons and linen.\nOccasionally turn clothing and household articles during boiling.\nClothing and household articles to be boiled must be washed and rinsed thoroughlybefore boiling."}, {"page": 67, "text": "Activity 6\nLet us do (in groups)\nWith the guidance of your teacher, practise use of a disinfectant as a method ofdisinfecting clothes.\nRequirements\nBasins, soap, water, pegs, socks, disinfectant, source of heat andsufuria\n.\nWhat to do\n1.\nSoak the socks in cold water for about 20 minutes to loosen dirt.\n2.\nRemove the socks from the soaking water. Squeeze out excess water.\n3.\nWash the socks gently in the warm soapy water.\n4.\nRinse the socks in warm water. Rinse them again in cold water.\n5.\nAdd disinfectant to the flnal cold rinsing water and rinse the socks.\n6.\nDry the socks on a clothesline. Secure them with pegs.\n7.\nRemove them from the clothesline when dry.\n8.\nFold and store them in a drawer.\nNote\nDisinfectant can be put in:\n1.\nThe soaking water: This is done when dealing with clothing or household articlesthat were exposed to infectious diseases.\n2.\nFinal rinsing water: Adding disinfectant to the flnal rinsing water ensures thatany remaining bacteria or viruses are eliminated."}, {"page": 68, "text": "et us\nLean\nLr\nDisinfectants are most suitable for fabrics that are damaged by boiling.\nCarefully read and follow the instructions provided by the manufacturer on thedisinfectant label.\nWear protective clothing such as gloves to avoid infections.\nSome disinfectants may require rinsing after application. Follow the instructions todetermine if rinsing is necessary, if so, follow the recommended rinsing process.\nActivity 7\nLet us do (in groups)\nWith the guidance of your teacher, practise sun drying and ironing to disinfect anapron.\nRequirements\nBasins, soap, water, pegs, white cotton apron, clothesline, ironing surface and iron box.\nWhat to do\n1.\nSoak the apron in cold water for 20 minutes.\n2.\nWash the apron in warm soapy water using friction method.\n3.\nRinse the apron in warm water to remove all traces of soap.\n4.\nRinse the apron in cold water to freshen it.\n5.\nDry the apron on a clothesline under the sun.\n6.\nRemove the apron from the clothesline while it is slightly damp."}, {"page": 69, "text": "7.\nIron the apron with a hot iron to disinfect and remove creases.\n8.\nAir the apron and store it in a clean dry place ready for use.\nActivity 8\nLet us do (in groups)\nGrade 9 learners researched on the internet for the procedure of disinfecting usingsalting method. Read their flndings.\nDisinfecting using salting method\nRequirements\nBasins, soap, water, pegs, handkerchief, clothesline, ironing surface and iron box.\nWhat to do\n1.\nPut a jug of warm water in a basin and add two tablespoons of table saltto the warm water.\n2.\nStir the salt in the warm water until it completely dissolves. This creates asalt solution with disinfectant properties.\n3.\nSoak the handkerchief in the salty water, ensuring that it is fully immersedin the water.\n4.\nAllow the handkerchief to soak for twenty minutes. This gives the saltenough time to work as a disinfectant.\n5.\nRub the handkerchief gently to remove mucus. Remove the handkerchieffrom the salty water.\n6.\nWash the handkerchief in warm soapy water. Rinse the handkerchief inwarm water.\n7.\nMake the flnal rinse in cold salty water to disinfect the handkerchief further.\n8.\nWring the handkerchief gently to remove excess water.\n9.\nHang the handkerchief on a clothesline and secure it with pegs.\nUse the procedure to disinfect a handkerchief using salting."}, {"page": 70, "text": "Importance of disinfecting clothing and household articles\nActivity 9\nLet us talk (in pairs)\nLilians family is caring for their grandmother, Mrs Kate, who is suffering from aninfectious disease. Lilian has observed that her grandmothers clothings, beddingsand towels are laundered separately. They are also thoroughly disinfected.\n1.\nWhy do you think it is important for Mrs Kates clothing, towels and beddingsto be disinfected?\n2.\nShare your points in class.\nActivity 10\nLet us debate\n1.\nOrganise the classroom for a debate.\n2.\nDebate on the following topic:\nRegular disinfection of clothing and householdarticles is necessary for maintaining a healthy living environment.\n3.\nRecord the presentations made during the debate.\nActivity 11\nLet us do (in groups)\n1.\nMake posters on the importance of disinfecting personal items (handkerchiefs,\nsocks, towels, gloves, aprons and dustcoats).\n2.\nDisplay the posters on the school noticeboard to create awareness.\net us\nLean\nLr\nThe following are the importance of disinfecting clothing and household articles:\n1.\nPrevents infections: Disinfecting clothes and household articles helps kill germswhich reduce the risk of spreading communicable diseases.\n2.\nPromotes personal hygiene: Disinfecting clothes and household articles is crucialin enhancing personal hygiene.\n3.\nPrevents cross contamination: Disinfecting clothing is important after exposureto areas that may be contaminated such as hospitals or public transportation,\nto minimise the risk of carrying viruses and bacteria into the home.\n4.\nSpecial groups of people may be vulnerable to infections. Therefore, disinfectingclothing and household articles is crucial in households with special groups ofpeople to protect their health. Special groups of people include expectant women,\nchildren, the elderly and the sick."}, {"page": 71, "text": "Assess yourself\n1.\nGrade 9 learners are making a presentation to educate members of theircommunity on disinfecting clothing and household articles. Explain the methodsof disinfecting they are likely to include in their presentation.\n2.\nYou have been tasked to disinfect a cotton towel of a person suffering from ahighly infectious skin disease.\na)\nWhich method of disinfecting would you use? Explain your reasons.\nb)\nWhich safety precautions would you observe when disinfecting the towel?\nc)\nWrite down the procedure of the disinfection method you chose."}, {"page": 72, "text": "In this strand, we will learn how to carry out grafting. We will also construct a homemadesun dryer for preserving vegetables.\nGrafting in Plants\nGrafting is a technique used in crop production. Grafting is done by joining two parts ofclosely related plants so that they grow as one plant. When they are joined, the plant iscalled a grafted plant. The upper part of the graft is called a scion while the lower part iscalled a rootstock. Grafting can be done on crops such as fruit plants and also on flowers.\nscionroot stock\nParts of a grafted plantgraft union\nA grafted mango seedling\nActivity 1\nLet us go digital\nUse digital devices or books and magazines to search for examples of plants thatcan be grafted. In your search, observe the parts that are cut from each plant andhow they are tied together to form one plant. Then, discuss the following questions.\n1.\nWhich are examples of plants that can be grafted?\n2.\nWhat could have been the main reason for grafting the plants that you havestudied observed?\nPRODUCTION TECHNIQUES"}, {"page": 73, "text": "Carrying out grafting for various reasons\nGrafting may be done in crops such as fruits and also on flowers. On flowers such asrose and bougainvillea, it can be done to produce more than one variety of flower colour.\nOn fruit plants, it can be done to ensure that they mature faster by obtaining the scionfrom a fast maturing food crop. It can also be done to get improved variety of fruits,\nto produce a fruit plant that can resist some diseases or a plant that can tolerate harshenvironment. Grafting can also be done to repair a damaged plant or to rejuvenate\n(renew growth of)\nan old plant.\nCarrying out grafting\nHow is grafting carried out?\nActivity 2\nLet us do (in groups)\nSearch for plants such as rose flowers, bougainvillea, mango, orange, lemon, lime,\navocado or any other plants of your choice. Your teacher will guide you to determineplants that can successfully be grafted and explain to you the main reason for graftingthe selected plants.\nGraft the plant by doing the following:\n1.\nSelect a healthy plant that has the qualities you desire, for example, a mangotree that produces sweet tasting mango fruits. You will cut the scion from theselected plant.\n2.\nSelect a healthy growing seedling to be your root stock, for example, a vigorouslygrowing seedling that grows well in your local area.\n3.\nSelect a branch from the desired plant. Cut a small branch that has some nodesor buds that can produce leaves. It should match the diameter of the root stockseedling.\n4.\nMake a sharp V-shaped cut at the top of the rootstock seedling and a perfectlytting shape on the base of the scion as shown in the pictures below."}, {"page": 74, "text": "While cutting the scion and rootstock, use a sharp tool to achieve a smooth cut.\nTake care of your fingers when cutting to avoid injuries.\n5.\nInsert the scion on the rootstock and tie the union tightly. Seal the union usingwax or any other suitable sealant to prevent entry of water as shown below.\n6.\nWrap the graft union using grafting tape to further secure the union from water.\nEntry of water in the graft union leads to rotting, hence death of the scion.\nCaring for the grafted seedling\nA grafted plant requires care to ensure that the graft union grows successfully. If theplant is neglected, the scion dies and falls off from the rootstock.\nActivity 3\nLet us do (in groups)\nCarry out the following activities to ensure that the grafted plant grows successfully.\n1.\nProtecting the plant: Construct a structure that protects the grafted plant frominterferences. Avoid touching the graft union to prevent weakening the union.\n2.\nWatering the plant: Irrigate the plant regularly to prevent the plant from waterstress. This ensures the plant system supplies nutrients to the growing scionfor leaves to grow from the buds. Ensure that you do not splash water on thegraft union.\n3.\nRemoving other buds: Remove any other buds that may grow below the graftunion (in the root stock). This ensures that only the desired branch grows onthe plant.\n4.\nRemoval of graft tape: Once the buds have grown into leaves and the graftunion is fully healed, remove the graft tape to allow the scion to grow widerand stronger."}, {"page": 75, "text": "Activity 4\nLet us talk (in groups)\n1.\nDiscuss the plants that you can graft for the following reasons.\na)\nBeauty at the homestead.\nb)\nFruit production at home.\nc)\nFor sale to your neighbours.\n2.\nYour sister, Jane, who is in Grade 4, planted an orange seedling in the schoolcompound. One day, a Grade 1 boy unintentionally stepped on the youngseedling and broke it into two pieces. Jane caught up with the young boy andreported him to you. Discuss how you would resolve the conflict and ensurethat Janes orange seedling project continues.\nImportance of grafting plantset us\nLean\nLr\nIn the previous activities, we have learnt that grafting can be done for the followingreasons:\n1.\nTo get desired quality of fruits.\n2.\nTo grow a single plant that produces a variety of fruits or flowers for beautypurposes. This increases aesthetic value of plants in the homestead.\n3.\nTo repair damaged seedlings or plants.\nAssess yourself\n1.\nState five reasons for grafting plants.\n2.\nExplain how you can repair a damaged mango seedling.\n3.\nYou neighbour has a new variety of colourful rose flower plants. Your parentshave asked you to establish a new variety of rose flower to replace an oldwhite rose flower in the homestead. Explain how you can help your parents toachieve this purpose.\n4.\nName the parts of a grafted avocado seedling described by the followingstatements:\na.\nThe upper part of the grafted seedling.\nb.\nThe lower part of the grafted seedling.\nc.\nThe place that is tied with grafting tape to join and seal the graftedseedling.\n5.\nOutline four practices carried out in caring for a grafted seedling to ensuresuccessful growth of the plant.\n6.\nWhat care should one take when carrying out grafting to ensure safety fromsharp grafting tools?"}, {"page": 76, "text": "Homemade Sun Dryer\nVegetables are important sources of nutrients that should be included in every meal. Weshould therefore grow vegetables at home to ensure their availability in our meals. Duringthe rainy seasons, some vegetables grow in plenty. However, many vegetables, especiallythe green leafy ones have a short storage life. We can preserve the vegetables to beused throughout the year by sun-drying method. Drying the vegetables for preservationrequire the use of a sun dryer in order to retain the quality of vegetables. How can wemake a sun dryer to dry the vegetables for preservation?\nSearching for information on Homemade sun dryer\nActivity 1\nLet us do( in groups)\nUse books, magazines, digital devices or enquire from a knowledgeable person howto make a homemade sun dryer for vegetables. In your search for information,\nobserve the parts of a homemade sun dryer, the materials used to make it and theappropriate size that one can make using locally available materials. Then, discussthe following questions.\n1.\nWhich vegetables can you dry for preservation using a homemade sun dryer?\n2.\nWhich materials can you use to construct a homemade sun dryer for vegetables?\n3.\nWhat structure do you require to construct the sun dryer?\n4.\nWhy should households dry vegetables using a homemade sun dryer?\nConstruction of a homemade sun dryer for vegetablepreservation\nA homemade sun dryer can be made using locally available materials. All that is requiredis an understanding of how to dry the green vegetables without over-exposing thevegetables to direct sunlight in order to conserve most of their nutrients, colour and taste.\nThe locally available materials can be acquired from the remains of construction materialsused for other purposes at home or in school. The design of the structure requires a framestructure with the shape of your choice and enclosing materials such as polythene sheetor glass to allow passage of sunlight. The sunlight brings in heat energy from the sunto drain excess moisture from the vegetables. A holding tray can be constructed usingwire mesh to hold the vegetables inside the structure and allow free circulation of heatenergy while drying the vegetables.\nBefore starting the construction, make a sketch of the homemade sun dryer. Use theideas that you have gained so far. List the materials that you can use based on what isavailable in your environment."}, {"page": 77, "text": "Activity 2\nLet us do (in groups)\n1.\nSketch and construct a supportive frame structure using pieces of wood orstrong wires to form the shape of your choice. The size depends on the quantityof vegetables you would like to preserve at once.\n2.\nConstruct a vegetable holding tray using a screen mesh and install it insidethe frame structure. You can make this using a wire net or any other nettingmaterial. The number of trays depend on the size of your structure.\n3.\nCover the frame structure using a material that allows passage of sunlight.\nThis part can be made using a clear polythene sheet. The enclosed structureshould form a small cage that concentrates sunlight inside it so as to work likea greenhouse structure.\n4.\nPlace the constructed sun dryer in an exposed area that receives adequatesunlight throughout the day. Place a thermometer on the tray inside the sundryer. Observe the temperature inside the sun dryer after a period of aboutone hour.\nHomemade sun dryer\nYou can determine whether the sun dryer is functioning properly by comparing theexternal temperature with the internal temperature (temperature inside the sun dryer)\nafter placing the thermometer on the tray for a period of time. Alternatively you canweigh the vegetables before putting them in the sun dryer and after putting theminside for sometime and compare the weights."}, {"page": 78, "text": "Using the sun dryer to dry vegetables for preservation\nOnce the sun dryer has been constructed and tested, it can be used to dry green vegetablesfor preservation purposes. To use the dryer:\n1.\nClean the constructed dryer by wiping it with clean soapy water and rinse it bywiping with a rinsed moist piece of cloth. Remember to clean the holding trayas well.\n2.\nPlace the sun dryer in a suitable clean environment with adequate exposure tosunlight throughout the day.\n3.\nTake some clean dry leafy vegetables and arrange them on the tray insidethe dryer. Ensure they are arranged in single layer and evenly spread to allowadequate air circulation.\n4.\nClose the sun dryers entry (door) to trap the heat inside the sun dryer.\n5.\nCheck the drying vegetables after some few hours and turn them to ensure theydry evenly. The drying period may vary from a few days to a week dependingon the weather conditions and the amount of moisture in the vegetables.\n6.\nRemove the vegetables from the sun dryer once they are dried and put them ina tightly closed container for preservation.\nCaution\nObserve personal hygiene when handling the vegetables.\nEnsure the vegetables put in the sun dryer are clean and free from contamination.\nWhen it is very cold, especially at night, put the sun dryer inside a room to protectyour vegetables.\nTake Home Activity\nAfter learning how to construct and use a homemade sun dryer, you can make a sun dryerof a size that suits your home use. You can seek your parent,s or guardians support inacquiring available materials and constructing a sun dryer at home to be used by yourfamily. This way, you will be a responsible person who can help your family membersand friends to enhance food security at family level."}, {"page": 79, "text": "Assess yourself\n1.\nWhat is a vegetable sun dryer?\n2.\nSome vegetables are often in surplus during the rainy season.\na.\nExplain the use of a sun dryer in enhancing food security.\nb.\nApart from ensuring food security, give other reasons why the use ofhomemade sun dryers should be adopted in our homes.\n3.\nList four leafy vegetables that can be dried for preservation.\n4.\nName two materials that can be used to construct the following parts of a sundryer for vegetables.\na.\nThe frame structure: _________________ or ___________________\nb.\nThe tray: ________________________ or _____________________\nc.\nThe dryer covering: ______________________ or _______________\n5.\nGive two reasons for each of the following parts of a sun dryera.\nThe transparent covering.\nb.\nThe tray.\n6.\nExplain the importance of the following practices in sun drying vegetables.\na.\nCleaning the dryer.\nb.\nCleaning the vegetables.\nc.\nPlacing the drier in exposed sunlight."}]};
